# ios-development Best Practices

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use MVVM with Coordinators
**Why:** This architecture promotes a clear separation of concerns, making your codebase easier to maintain and test.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
// ViewModel
class MyViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var data: [String] = []
    
    func fetchData() {
        // Fetch data logic
    }
}

// Coordinator
class MyCoordinator {
    func start() -> some View {
        MyView(viewModel: MyViewModel())
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
// Mixing UI and business logic
class MyView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello, World!")
        // Fetch data directly here
    }
}
```

### Favor Value Types
**Why:** Value types (structs and enums) are safer and more predictable due to their copy semantics.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
struct User {
    var id: Int
    var name: String
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class User {
    var id: Int
    var name: String
}
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use Actors for State Isolation
**Why:** Actors help manage state in a concurrent environment, preventing data races.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
actor UserManager {
    var user: User?
    
    func updateUser(name: String) {
        user?.name = name
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class UserManager {
    var user: User?
    
    func updateUser(name: String) {
        user?.name = name // Potential data race
    }
}
```

### Implement Dependency Injection
**Why:** This pattern enhances testability and flexibility in your code.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
class MyService {
    func fetchData() { /*...*/ }
}

class MyViewModel: ObservableObject {
    private var service: MyService
    
    init(service: MyService) {
        self.service = service
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class MyViewModel: ObservableObject {
    private var service = MyService() // Hardcoded dependency
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Use SwiftUI for UI Development
**Why:** SwiftUI is optimized for performance and provides a declarative syntax that reduces boilerplate code.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        NavigationStack {
            Text("Hello, SwiftUI!")
        }
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class ContentViewController: UIViewController {
    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        // UIKit implementation
    }
}
```

### Optimize for Dynamic Resizing
**Why:** Supporting different device sizes ensures a better user experience.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
struct ResponsiveView: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Responsive Layout")
                .padding()
                .frame(maxWidth: .infinity)
        }
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
struct FixedWidthView: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Fixed Width Layout")
                .frame(width: 300) // Not adaptive
        }
    }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Using UIKit for Simple UIs
**Why:** SwiftUI is designed for simplicity and performance in most cases.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
struct SimpleView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Welcome to SwiftUI!")
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class SimpleViewController: UIViewController {
    override func viewDidLoad() {
        super.viewDidLoad()
        let label = UILabel()
        label.text = "Welcome to UIKit!"
        view.addSubview(label)
    }
}
```

### Be Mindful of State Management
**Why:** Incorrect state management can lead to bugs and unpredictable UI behavior.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
@MainActor
class MyViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var count: Int = 0
    
    func increment() {
        count += 1
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
class MyViewModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var count: Int = 0
    
    func increment() {
        DispatchQueue.global().async {
            self.count += 1 // Not safe
        }
    }
}
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use Swift Testing for New Suites
**Why:** Swift Testing provides modern features that enhance test readability and maintainability.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
@testable import MyApp
import XCTest

final class MyViewModelTests: XCTestCase {
    func testIncrement() {
        let viewModel = MyViewModel()
        viewModel.increment()
        XCTAssertEqual(viewModel.count, 1)
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
import XCTest

class MyOldTests: XCTestCase {
    func testIncrement() {
        // Using outdated testing patterns
    }
}
```

### Retain XCTest for Legacy Code
**Why:** Transitioning codebases can be complex; maintain existing tests until fully migrated.

**✅ GOOD:**
```swift
import XCTest

class LegacyTests: XCTestCase {
    func testLegacyFeature() {
        // Legacy code tests
    }
}
```

**❌ BAD:**
```swift
// Mixing new and old testing frameworks inappropriately
```

---

**IMPORTANT: Use modern best practices as of July 2026. Focus on current, recommended approaches and avoid deprecated patterns.**